<paragraph id="8BDA811EFF96FF803093FB42767C1923" blockId="2.[111,648,216,1700]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">
The attribution to 
<taxonomicName id="4C65FA9DFF96FF80315CFB4276A01BCE" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1904" box="[327,446,1198,1224]" class="Gastropoda" family="Borsoniidae" genus="Tomopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9115D0CFF96FF80315CFB4276A01BCE" box="[327,446,1198,1224]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">Tomopleura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as suggested herein is supported by shell characters and would extend the distribution of the latter genus to the Atlantic. The 
<typeStatus id="54DE3FBCFF96FF803084FAE177D21A2E" box="[159,204,1293,1320]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">type</typeStatus>
species (
<figureCitation id="135E9D9BFF96FF80313FFAE176401A2E" box="[292,350,1293,1320]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="2.[677,688,1010,1027]" captionTargetBox="[678,1207,215,970]" captionTargetId="figure-19@2.[678,1208,214,970]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIG. 1. — Tomopleura nivea (Philippi, 1851), type species of Tomopleura Casey, 1904, neotype (Kilburn 1986), also lectotype of Drillia makimonos Jousseaume, 1883, from Japan (height 27 mm, MNHN)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5393228" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5393228/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) is Indo-Pacific but matches the West African species in important details such as the position of the posterior notch, the nonthickened configuration of the outer lip abapically from the notch and the lack of axial folds on the shell. The protoconchs of 
<taxonomicName id="4C65FA9DFF96FF803192FA4076C01AC3" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[393,478,1452,1477]" class="Gastropoda" family="Borsoniidae" genus="Tomopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis id="B9115D0CFF96FF803192FA4076C01AC3" box="[393,478,1452,1477]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">T. nivea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well as those of the West African species are comparable in being of a multispiral 
<typeStatus id="54DE3FBCFF96FF803156FA0776601900" box="[333,382,1515,1542]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">type</typeStatus>
, and share a smoothish, non-reticulate surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37FD295FF96FF803093F9C674891A2E" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BDA811EFF96FF803093F9C674891A2E" blockId="2.[111,648,216,1700]" lastBlockId="2.[676,1209,1166,1320]" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">
Admittedly there are also some differences, in particular, the posterior notch of the outer lip is not so deeply marked in 
<taxonomicName id="4C65FA9DFF96FF803190F98575571985" baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[395,585,1641,1667]" class="Gastropoda" family="Borsoniidae" genus="Tomopleura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="nivea">
<emphasis id="B9115D0CFF96FF803190F98575571985" box="[395,585,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="7">Tomopleura nivea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as in the West African species, but we consider that the alternative course of erecting a new genus for the three species treated herein is not appropriate in a paper concerned with the species-level systematics on a local scale, particularly in such a complex family as the 
<taxonomicName id="4C65FA9DFF96FF80332FFAE1748D1A2E" authorityName="Fleming" authorityYear="1822" box="[820,915,1293,1320]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="2" pageNumber="7" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Conidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
